@@eThe Paladin Tradition@@N

@@yThe Sundering Wars@@N
Paladins were born from a specific crisis. During the Sundering Wars, mortal armies
desecrated temples, treating sacred spaces as tactically useful terrain rather than
protected ground. Under the Charter of Passage, temples had been neutral ground,
inviolable by any party because their neutrality served everyone's long-term
interests. The Sundering Wars' combatants either could not enforce these protections
or chose not to. The clerics who watched this happen and resolved never to leave
their sanctuaries defenseless again became the first Paladins.

@@yThe Oath Is the Institution@@N
These clerics did not become soldiers. Soldiers serve commanders. The first Paladins
swore oaths to the light itself, the covenant, the maintenance of conditions under
which sacred practice can occur. The oath overrides loyalty to any particular
commander or institution. The tradition maintains extensive archives of historical
oath-mark decisions, situations where a Paladin's reading of covenant conflicted
with civil or military orders. These case studies form the core of advanced
training, including cases where Paladins exercised oath-authority and were, in
retrospect, wrong. The tradition does not suppress these. They are considered the
most important teaching material.

@@yThe Shield-Wardens@@N
The Solar Court's temple-guard auxiliaries are claimed as an earlier ancestor: those
who stood at the threshold between battle-clergy and ceremonial ministry. The
shield-warden role, holding every threshold against the dark, is the Paladin
tradition's self-image. The advance-and-sanctify doctrine extends shield-warden
logic to mobile contexts: you advance to extend the ground that sacred practice can
safely occupy, and you sanctify as you advance so the ground you hold is genuinely
protected rather than merely defended.

@@yThe Partnership with Priests@@N
The Hour of Quiet Thunder schism created the Paladin-Priest partnership. Paladins
advance and create secure ground; Priests sustain healing within it. The timing of
these functions requires continuous negotiation: a Paladin who advances too
aggressively exposes the Priest's position, while a Priest who works too slowly
constrains the Paladin's options. Trust calibration between partners is taught
formally and refined through accumulated operational experience.
